<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This definition captures the strongest meaningful form of the localist position. A system is globally well-behaved by virtue of excluding a bounded family of local obstructions. When such a characterization exists, global consistency is in fact reducible to local enforcement.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The question is therefore not whether local constraints ever suffice, but rather when they suffice.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\begin{theorem}[Finite-Type Boundary]
Let <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="script">L</mi><mo>ŌŖå</mo><mi mathvariant="script">H</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">  \mathcal{L} \subseteq \mathcal{H}  </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.8193em; vertical-align: -0.136em;"></span><span class="mord mathcal">L</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">ŌŖå</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathcal" style="margin-right: 0.00965em;">H</span></span></span></span> be a prefix-closed language of admissible histories. Then the following are equivalent:
\begin{enumerate}
\item There exists a bounded-window constraint system deciding admissibility of every extension using only the most recent <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">  k  </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6944em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.03148em;">k</span></span></span></span> symbols for some finite <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">  k  </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6944em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.03148em;">k</span></span></span></span>.
\item The language <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="script">L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">  \mathcal{L}  </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathcal">L</span></span></span></span> is <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">  k  </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6944em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.03148em;">k</span></span></span></span>-local for some finite <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">  k  </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6944em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.03148em;">k</span></span></span></span>.
\item The admissibility structure of <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="script">L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">  \mathcal{L}  </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathcal">L</span></span></span></span> is representable as a safety language of finite type.
\end{enumerate}
\end{theorem}</p>
