<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This theorem isolates the precise locus of structural non-equivalence. The issue is not simply whether a system remembers enough, but whether the admissibility relation itself is of finite type. If it is, then local rules suffice in principle. If it is not, then no finite local mechanism, regardless of engineering sophistication, can recover global consistency exactly.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The significance of this distinction becomes clearer when one considers examples. Histories satisfying nearest-neighbor exclusion on a lattice form a finite-type system. Histories whose admissibility depends on exact matching of arbitrarily distant commitments do not. Likewise, a type system whose constraints reduce to finitely generated local derivation rules is finite-type; a system requiring compatibility with all prior commitments in a non-compressible manner is not.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The earlier critique that ŌĆ£this is only memoryŌĆØ is therefore correct only for languages at or below the finite-type boundary. In that regime, global consistency is reducible to bounded local checking, and nothing stronger should be claimed. The present framework becomes nontrivial only for those admissibility structures that lie above that boundary, namely those whose consistency condition is not finitely local.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">One may sharpen the distinction further by considering summary maps rather than contiguous windows.</p>
