for all <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi><mo separator="true">,</mo><msup><mi>H</mi><mo mathvariant="normal" lspace="0em" rspace="0em">ŌĆ▓</mo></msup><mo>Ōłł</mo><mi mathvariant="script">L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">  H,H' \in \mathcal{L}  </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.9463em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.08125em;">H</span><span class="mpunct">,</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.1667em;"></span><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.08125em;">H</span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.7519em;"><span style="top: -3.063em; margin-right: 0.05em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 2.7em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight"><span class="mord mtight">ŌĆ▓</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">Ōłł</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathcal">L</span></span></span></span>.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\begin{theorem}[Summary Reduction Criterion]
A finite summary map <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>Žā</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">  \sigma  </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.4306em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.03588em;">Žā</span></span></span></span> is admissibility-complete if and only if the admissibility language <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="script">L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">  \mathcal{L}  </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathcal">L</span></span></span></span> factors through a finite right-congruence on prefixes.
\end{theorem}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\begin{proof}
If <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>Žā</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">  \sigma  </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.4306em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.03588em;">Žā</span></span></span></span> is admissibility-complete, then equality of summaries induces an equivalence relation on histories under which admissible continuation sets are identical. This is precisely a right-congruence with finite index. Conversely, any finite-index right-congruence induces a summary map by sending each history to its equivalence class, and admissibility is then determined by the class.
\end{proof}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">This criterion makes precise the relationship between finite summaries and structural reducibility. The existence of a finite sufficient statistic is not guaranteed merely by path dependence. It is guaranteed only when the admissibility language admits a finite right-congruence. In automata-theoretic terms, this is exactly the boundary between regular and non-regular admissibility structure.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">We may now formulate the decisive conclusion.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\begin{theorem}[Structural Non-Equivalence]
Let <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="script">L</mi><mo>ŌŖå</mo><mi mathvariant="script">H</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">  \mathcal{L} \subseteq \mathcal{H}  </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.8193em; vertical-align: -0.136em;"></span><span class="mord mathcal">L</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">ŌŖå</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathcal" style="margin-right: 0.00965em;">H</span></span></span></span> be a prefix-closed admissibility language. If <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant="script">L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">  \mathcal{L}  </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathcal">L</span></span></span></span> is neither of finite type nor representable by a finite right-congruence, then:
[
\text{no bounded local system and no finite summary system can enforce } \mathcal{L} \text{ exactly.}
]
\end{theorem}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">\begin{proof}
Failure of finite type excludes bounded-window enforcement by the Failure of Local Reduction theorem. Failure of finite right-congruence excludes exact finite-summary enforcement by the Summary Reduction Criterion. Hence neither class of reduced systems suffices.
\end{proof}</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The relevance of this result is not terminological. It establishes a genuine trichotomy.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">First, there are systems whose admissibility is finitely local; such systems are fully reducible to local constraint enforcement. Second, there are systems whose admissibility is not finitely local but does admit a finite sufficient summary; such systems are nonlocal in presentation but regular in structure. Third, there are systems whose admissibility is neither finitely local nor finitely summarizable; such systems are genuinely history-binding in the strong sense and cannot be reduced without loss.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">It is only in this third regime that the present framework acquires nontrivial force. Below that boundary, the criticism that one has merely renamed memory, path dependence, or bounded verification is mathematically correct. Above it, the criticism fails, because the admissibility structure itself no longer factors through any finite local or finite summary representation.</p>
<p dir="auto" class="break-words" node="[object Object]" style="white-space: pre-wrap;">In this sense the correct conclusion is not that local systems never yield global consistency, nor that all path-dependent systems are structurally distinct. The correct conclusion is sharper: the nontrivial content of binding systems begins exactly where admissibility ceases to be of finite type and ceases to admit finite right-congruence reduction. That boundary, rather than generic appeal to memory or history, is the proper locus of the theory.</p></div></div><section class="inline-media-container flex flex-col gap-1 clear-both"></section><section class="auth-notification flex flex-col gap-1"></section></div></div><div class="order-first sticky hidden @md/mainview:block top-11 h-0 opacity-0 group-focus-within:opacity-100 group-hover:opacity-100 -mr-[36px] @lg/mainview:-mr-12"><div class="min-h-7 py-4 flex flex-col gap-0.5"><button class="inline-flex items-center justify-center gap-2 whitespace-nowrap text-sm font-medium leading-[normal] cursor-pointer focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-1 focus-visible:ring-ring disabled:opacity-60 disabled:cursor-not-allowed transition-colors duration-100 [&amp;_svg]:shrink-0 select-none text-fg-secondary hover:text-fg-primary hover:bg-button-ghost-hover disabled:hover:text-fg-secondary disabled:hover:bg-transparent [&amp;_svg]:hover:text-fg-primary h-10 w-10 rounded-full" type="button" aria-label="Edit" data-state="closed"><span style="opacity: 1; transform: none;"><svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="stroke-[2] size-4"><path d="M18.25 5.75C16.8693 4.36929 14.6307 4.36929 13.25 5.75L10.125 8.875L5.52404 13.476C4.86236 14.1376 4.45361 15.0104 4.36889 15.9423L4 20.0001L8.0578 19.6311C8.98967 19.5464 9.86234 19.1377 10.524 18.476L18.25 10.75C19.6307 9.36929 19.6307 7.13071 18.25 5.75V5.75Z" stroke="currentColor"></path><path d="M12.5 7.5L16.5 11.5" stroke="currentColor">